WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.547
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:05.214 --> 00:00:06.630
TOM FLETCHER: Thank
you very much.

00:00:06.630 --> 00:00:08.860
And thank you all
for coming out today.

00:00:08.860 --> 00:00:10.720
And I think what
we're going to do

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:13.010
on the format is that
I'll just give you

00:00:13.010 --> 00:00:18.750
a quick overview of my
journey to get to this point,

00:00:18.750 --> 00:00:22.470
and say a couple of things
about this book which

00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:24.780
I've had to resign to publish.

00:00:24.780 --> 00:00:26.761
And so I'll explain
a bit about that.

00:00:26.761 --> 00:00:28.260
But what I'm most
interested in then

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:31.370
is getting the conversation
into more of a Q and A.

00:00:31.370 --> 00:00:34.420
But in particular, I've
been doing these events now

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:35.430
this last week.

00:00:35.430 --> 00:00:37.660
And at every single
event, people

00:00:37.660 --> 00:00:39.147
have spoken to me about Google.

00:00:39.147 --> 00:00:40.730
I've been talking
to them about power,

00:00:40.730 --> 00:00:44.280
and they've come right back
at me and talked about Google.

00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:46.250
And I really want
to just reflect

00:00:46.250 --> 00:00:49.880
on what that means in terms
of a power transition,

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:55.860
and what there is that we can
do together in that space, what

00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:56.780
the challenges are.

00:00:56.780 --> 00:01:00.620
And there are huge challenges
around trust, authenticity,

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:05.140
and authority there that
I'd love to talk about.

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:07.260
But really just open
it up at that point.

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:10.300
And we can talk about
just about anything

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:14.740
you'd like to, whether it's
this crazy period of four

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:17.080
years working with those
three prime ministers--

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:19.420
the end of Blair, the
whole of Gordon Brown,

00:01:19.420 --> 00:01:22.334
and the first year
of David Cameron.

00:01:22.334 --> 00:01:25.100
Or then the four
years after that,

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:27.850
when I was in Beirut,
and trying to use

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.415
these amazing new tools--
the smartphone superpower--

00:01:31.415 --> 00:01:33.500
to do diplomacy in
a different way,

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:35.920
and to connect with
people in a way

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:38.490
that we've never been
able to do before.

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:42.311
And I can give you some examples
of how all that happened.

00:01:42.311 --> 00:01:43.810
If you want, we can
go back further.

00:01:43.810 --> 00:01:48.250
We can talk about my
life as a failed boxer.

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:51.599
I lost a boxing match
in Nairobi to the mayor,

00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:53.140
and they had t-shirts
made up saying,

00:01:53.140 --> 00:01:54.556
Fletcher goes home
on a stretcher,

00:01:54.556 --> 00:01:56.710
which I pretty much did.

00:01:56.710 --> 00:01:58.850
We can talk about my
career as a failed lead

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:03.890
singer for Freshly Squeezed,
very much ahead of their time.

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:07.460
Or indeed, anything
you'd like to cover.

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:14.660
So the book, "Naked Diplomacy,"
clearly no real nudity

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:16.270
involved.

00:02:16.270 --> 00:02:19.260
The idea-- stolen really
from Jamie Oliver--

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:22.440
is what does diplomacy
look like, in the way

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:24.360
that he did with cooking.

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:28.950
If you take away all of the
paraphernalia and all the crap

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:32.200
that holds us back, and we've
constructed around diplomacy--

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:34.360
which is a very kind
of maps and chaps

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:39.750
world-- a load of etiquette,
and protocol, and language,

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:43.090
which I'm arguing isn't helping
us to connect with people.

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:46.040
But in a way, I'm
preaching to the choir

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:50.550
here, because you're disrupting
us in that space already.

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:52.960
And one of the things
I say to diplomats

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:56.050
is unless we find a way to
communicate more effectively,

00:02:56.050 --> 00:02:58.580
and to use these new
tools and to strip away

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:03.880
a lot of this rubbish, the kind
of platitudes about Britain

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:06.970
and Cambodia have warm,
bilateral relations

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:09.847
on a range of mutual-- I mean,
that stuff that just switches

00:03:09.847 --> 00:03:10.680
you off immediately.

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.630
Unless we can shift all
of that, scrape those

00:03:13.630 --> 00:03:17.900
barnacles off the boat,
then you-- and we often

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:21.110
use Google in this context--
will disrupt us even more.

00:03:21.110 --> 00:03:22.760
And I often ask
people, who do you

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:25.320
think will be more
powerful in 10 years time,

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:26.770
Google or Britain?

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:29.230
Who would you have on the
Security Council in 10 years

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.719
time, Google or Britain?

00:03:31.719 --> 00:03:33.760
And increasingly, people--
we do a show of hands.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:35.976
I won't do it here,
because you're very loyal.

00:03:35.976 --> 00:03:37.395
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:37.395 --> 00:03:40.740
And word would go back
very quickly to Eric

00:03:40.740 --> 00:03:42.360
that whoever voted for Britain.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:46.430
But the number of hands
that go up for Google

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:49.540
is increasing every
time I ask the question.

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:55.479
So that's the idea of the
naked in "Naked Diplomacy."

00:03:55.479 --> 00:03:57.520
And obviously, because
I'm trying to sell a book,

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.830
we do chuck in a few
stories about nudity anyway.

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:03.180
There's a story about when my
son turned up at the PM's house

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:06.120
as a four-year-old
completely naked,

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:08.172
and the housekeeper came
to the door and said,

00:04:08.172 --> 00:04:10.130
you're the first guest
the prime minster's ever

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:11.540
had arrive naked.

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:15.400
A sign of how professional the
British foreign service is.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:19.589
There's a story in there about
the time I was at the G8 Summit

00:04:19.589 --> 00:04:22.389
with David Cameron--
his very first summit.

00:04:22.389 --> 00:04:24.430
And I don't know if it's
like this in your world,

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:27.200
but there's a kind of
physicality and theatricality

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:29.740
to the way that
leaders interact.

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:32.790
Think of Putin on his horse
and so on, and his tank.

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:36.042
And so I took David Cameron
swimming in the lake at Muskoka

00:04:36.042 --> 00:04:36.960
in Canada.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:39.180
So then we could brief the
other delegations, right?

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:42.550
There's a new kid on the
block here, strong and young--

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:45.170
a bit like the Justin
Trudeau effect now.

00:04:45.170 --> 00:04:48.160
So we did all that, briefed the
other delegations, fantastic.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:50.740
Word went round, and when
we arrived at the meeting,

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:53.750
Obama was feeling his muscles,
and Sarkozy was looking

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:55.130
a bit jealous, and so on.

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:56.890
Perfect.

00:04:56.890 --> 00:04:59.950
And then Berlusconi
saw this and was a bit

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:02.560
put out that someone else
was stealing that space.

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:05.320
And so he disappeared off and
came back 10 minutes later

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.820
with a stack of
photos of himself

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:12.786
lightly oiled and wearing a pair
of very, very tight Speedos.

00:05:12.786 --> 00:05:14.160
They were red, I
think-- though I

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:16.430
don't like to remember
the moment too much.

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:18.180
I've been trying to
forget it ever since--

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:20.230
and handed them around.

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:21.900
And for the only time
in my experience,

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.191
the leaders of the free world
were completely silenced.

00:05:24.191 --> 00:05:27.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:30.040
But the only other moment of
nudity in there, I'm afraid,

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:33.600
is actually more of the
core idea of the book, which

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:37.320
is that the very greatest
diplomat was actually

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:39.700
the very first diplomat,
and he was maybe

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:40.700
almost literally naked.

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:44.630
He was a prehistoric
man, probably a man.

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:47.330
And he was the first
person to convince

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:49.890
his fellow
Neanderthals to go out

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:53.550
hunting together rather than
clubbing them over the head.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:57.240
And that is these two basic
instincts we have for survival.

00:05:57.240 --> 00:06:01.250
One, survival of the fittest, to
compete for resource, and one,

00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:03.340
to go out and hunt together.

00:06:03.340 --> 00:06:07.820
And at it's basic
essence, that is what

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:10.320
diplomacy has been ever since.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:14.470
We're trying to provide those
compromises, the negotiations,

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:18.680
that help the human
species kind of rub along.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:21.370
And in the midst of all the
change that you're leading,

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:23.656
and I don't need
to tell you about,

00:06:23.656 --> 00:06:26.190
my argument is that diplomacy
is going to matter even

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.370
more than ever, because
you'll still need people,

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:31.888
as we go through this period
of enormous transition,

00:06:31.888 --> 00:06:34.910
fastest changes
ever, you'll still

00:06:34.910 --> 00:06:36.540
need people who
can help societies,

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:39.570
and states, and businesses,
and ideas rub along.

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:42.770
Because when we've gone through
even remotely similar periods

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:46.480
of change in the past--
think of the printing press--

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:49.210
it has led to centuries
of upheaval, and conflict,

00:06:49.210 --> 00:06:52.130
and war, and loss of
life on a massive scale.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:54.110
So somehow, we're
going to have to deal

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:56.780
with the consequences of
all this amazing stuff

00:06:56.780 --> 00:06:58.200
that you're doing.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:01.140
The unintended consequences
of the technological change

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:03.680
that you are leading will
be huge political and social

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:04.720
change.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:06.303
And so we're going
to need some people

00:07:06.303 --> 00:07:09.210
in there trying to help
us navigate through that.

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:11.610
And all that's
happening at a time

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:14.750
when my business of diplomacy
is itself being disrupted.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:17.190
I mentioned it's being
disrupted by you guys,

00:07:17.190 --> 00:07:19.560
but it's being disrupted
by many other actors

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:21.970
in the media, the
businesses that

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:24.070
have their own foreign policy.

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:27.070
I use the example often
of the Murdoch empire,

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:31.440
or even of Google, who actually
run a very, very efficient

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:34.280
foreign policy apparatus.

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:36.100
We're being disrupted
from all sides

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:39.140
and also from elsewhere
in our own governments.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:41.640
And so again, we're trying
to find ways to adapt,

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:46.330
to disrupt ourselves, so we
can still be competitive.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:48.960
But at the end of the day--
and this has been really

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:51.750
my journey, my lesson,
coming through Number 10

00:07:51.750 --> 00:07:55.250
and feeling that power
drain away, as time sped up,

00:07:55.250 --> 00:08:00.690
and we got adapted to 24/7
media and then social media.

00:08:00.690 --> 00:08:03.900
When I started, we cared about
140 words on the Sky ticker.

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.450
When I left Number 10, we
cared about 140 characters

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:07.380
on Twitter.

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:09.670
That whole sense of
speeding up, and how hard

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:12.630
it is now for government to
exercise the power we have.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:15.777
The result of all
that is that I've

00:08:15.777 --> 00:08:17.360
got to the point
where I've realized--

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:20.290
and you've worked it out
long before we have--

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:23.530
that we just simply don't have
the answers behind the wall.

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:25.720
And so we're going
to have to now form

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:29.510
these different kinds of
coalitions, unusual coalitions,

00:08:29.510 --> 00:08:32.610
in order to crack these
massive problems ahead of us--

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:34.789
around the next energy
source, around how do we

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:37.960
get 75 million kids
into school and out

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:41.080
of potentially suicide vests?

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:45.440
How do we find the balance
between security and liberty

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:46.850
online?

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:50.410
How do we judge when it's
right to go to war to protect

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:51.520
the most vulnerable?

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:54.890
Those are all issues that I'm
basically saying, admitting,

00:08:54.890 --> 00:08:57.004
we can't crack.

00:08:57.004 --> 00:08:58.420
And so we're going
to have to find

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:00.510
ways to work with
these new actors--

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:04.750
often in competitive space--
but find ways and synergies

00:09:04.750 --> 00:09:07.930
to try and crack those
problems together,

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:10.590
which is really where I'm
most interested in taking

00:09:10.590 --> 00:09:12.130
the conversation later.

00:09:12.130 --> 00:09:15.670
If diplomacy didn't
exist, my argument

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:18.270
is that we would
need to invent it,

00:09:18.270 --> 00:09:21.570
to deal with the consequences
of all this change.

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:27.020
But it's now much too important
to leave to the diplomats.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:32.416
So my case is that we need
others, including all of you,

00:09:32.416 --> 00:09:34.960
to think of yourselves
as citizen diplomats,

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:38.100
to feel that you also
have a responsibility

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:41.380
to promote
coexistence, to promote

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:43.750
that idea, like
my naked caveman,

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:48.550
that we can collaborate rather
than compete for resource.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:51.320
And this matters more than
ever now in the 21st century,

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.430
because the big dividing line
is not north versus south, east

00:09:55.430 --> 00:09:58.680
versus west, rich versus poor.

00:09:58.680 --> 00:10:01.750
The big dividing line now-- and
we see it in the Brexit debate,

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:04.700
we see it in the American
presidential campaign--

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:09.060
is between people who believe
in that coexistence-- rooms

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:12.300
like this, where you're
collaborating across cultures,

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:16.600
across races, across
religions, across ideas--

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:20.820
between those people, the
coexisters and the wall

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:21.350
builders.

00:10:21.350 --> 00:10:23.490
And on the wrong
side of the argument,

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:25.932
you've got Islamic
States, who don't just

00:10:25.932 --> 00:10:27.390
believe in attacking
the West, they

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:29.810
believe in attacking
the gray zone where

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:32.990
Islam and Christianity work
together, or live together.

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:34.980
You've got the hard
right in Europe

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:36.270
becoming louder than ever.

00:10:36.270 --> 00:10:37.740
You've got the
hard left in Europe

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:40.120
becoming louder than ever.

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:47.091
And of course, you have the wall
builder in chief, Donald Trump,

00:10:47.091 --> 00:10:50.750
arguing that basically the
answer to the 21st century

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:54.050
is just another layer of
bricks at the top of that wall.

00:10:54.050 --> 00:10:56.582
So these arguments
matter more than ever,

00:10:56.582 --> 00:10:58.790
but we need to build a much
bigger and more effective

00:10:58.790 --> 00:11:02.440
coalition than we've
ever had before if we're

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:04.490
going to find the answers
and the creativity

00:11:04.490 --> 00:11:08.990
and the ingenuity to help
us survive the 21st century.

00:11:08.990 --> 00:11:11.170
Sounds a dramatic way
to end it, but I think

00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:13.380
it is as important as that.

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:15.001
Thank you.

00:11:15.001 --> 00:11:18.160
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:20.225
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
fascinating introduction.

00:11:20.225 --> 00:11:22.350
One thing you talk about
in your book over and over

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:24.340
again is this idea
of citizen diplomacy

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:27.490
and how to avoid
armchair activism.

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:28.910
Can you start there?

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:30.285
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:11:30.285 --> 00:11:34.360
So my main worry
about social media

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:38.200
is the sort of
slacktivism side of it.

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:40.510
In Lebanon, we tried
a number of things

00:11:40.510 --> 00:11:43.720
to cut through to people in
completely different ways.

00:11:43.720 --> 00:11:47.586
So, for example, when the
Iranian embassy was blown up,

00:11:47.586 --> 00:11:51.440
rather than deliver a speech--
I couldn't go down and shake

00:11:51.440 --> 00:11:53.440
hands with the ambassador
because we didn't have

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.900
diplomatic relations-- I
went down and donated blood

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:59.890
and then tweeted the photo
and it went viral in Tehran.

00:11:59.890 --> 00:12:02.732
And it was one way of
showing the Iranian people

00:12:02.732 --> 00:12:05.190
that what they were being told
about Britain and the West--

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:07.580
you know, just challenge
it a little bit.

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:09.630
And so we found ways
to do things like that.

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:10.700
They were stunts.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:13.090
And many of my colleagues said
these are just ridiculous,

00:12:13.090 --> 00:12:14.190
attention-grabbing stunts.

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:16.727
But they were stunts
that had a purpose.

00:12:16.727 --> 00:12:18.310
We were trying to
use these new tools,

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:20.018
trying to build that
plane as we flew it,

00:12:20.018 --> 00:12:22.800
to find different ways to reach
out and connect with people

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:25.020
in a way my
predecessors could never

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:26.715
have done using
traditional media.

