00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:57.491
of social media.

00:22:57.491 --> 00:22:59.240
TOM FLETCHER: It's a
really good question.

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:00.948
It's a question that's
always been asked,

00:23:00.948 --> 00:23:03.530
of course, at every
stage of political change

00:23:03.530 --> 00:23:04.970
and democratization.

00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:07.690
And in the book, I've got
some kind of great quotes

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:09.250
from old diplomats
basically saying,

00:23:09.250 --> 00:23:12.410
the problem with
newspapers is that people

00:23:12.410 --> 00:23:14.510
will think they have some
influence over diplomacy

00:23:14.510 --> 00:23:15.009
and so on.

00:23:15.009 --> 00:23:16.700
And TV as well.

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:20.150
My argument is that if you
think the bottom line of my job,

00:23:20.150 --> 00:23:23.010
of diplomacy, is
trying to prevent

00:23:23.010 --> 00:23:24.552
people of [? dying ?] conflict.

00:23:24.552 --> 00:23:26.510
It's a very simple way
of trying to capture it.

00:23:26.510 --> 00:23:30.924
And at every moment when there's
been a greater democratization,

00:23:30.924 --> 00:23:33.090
where more people have had
greater oversight of what

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:36.650
I do, or we do in my
world, fewer people

00:23:36.650 --> 00:23:37.700
have died violently.

00:23:37.700 --> 00:23:40.170
And we're now, of
course, 200 times less

00:23:40.170 --> 00:23:42.820
likely to die violently
than 100 years ago.

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:46.590
So I see it on balance
as a positive thing.

00:23:46.590 --> 00:23:51.590
The empowerment of the
mob is a positive thing.

00:23:51.590 --> 00:23:53.820
But it does make my job harder.

00:23:53.820 --> 00:23:55.740
And August 2013 is
a classic example

00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:58.970
of that, the debate over whether
we should bomb Bashar al-Assad.

00:23:58.970 --> 00:24:02.620
Under the old rules, governments
had decided we'd do it.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:05.420
US, UK, in we go.

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:09.020
But, of course, the
reality was different.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:11.429
Post-Iraq, but also
in a social media

00:24:11.429 --> 00:24:13.220
age when people are
commenting in real time

00:24:13.220 --> 00:24:15.400
about the decisions
you're taking,

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:17.036
the UK parliament said no.

00:24:17.036 --> 00:24:20.780
And then, that gave Obama
reason to pause, and in the end,

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:21.940
not to do it either.

00:24:21.940 --> 00:24:25.007
And so, on balance, who knows?

00:24:25.007 --> 00:24:25.840
May be a good thing.

00:24:28.615 --> 00:24:30.740
The problem with making
judgments in foreign policy

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:32.654
is, of course, you
never have hindsight.

00:24:32.654 --> 00:24:34.320
But it's an example
of how actually it's

00:24:34.320 --> 00:24:39.480
harder if you're in the more
transparent West-- it's harder

00:24:39.480 --> 00:24:42.050
to do diplomacy because you
can't bluff in the same way.

00:24:42.050 --> 00:24:44.170
You can't win that-- kind
of that hand of poker

00:24:44.170 --> 00:24:47.590
against the more
autocratic regimes

00:24:47.590 --> 00:24:50.182
and against the Russians.

00:24:50.182 --> 00:24:52.640
FEMALE SPEAKER: I did like that
you note that not only does

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.780
Putin ride horseback, but
he has the biggest plane.

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:57.442
TOM FLETCHER: He has, by
far, the biggest plane.

00:24:57.442 --> 00:24:58.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]
diplomatic summit.

00:24:58.630 --> 00:24:59.980
TOM FLETCHER: You can read
all sorts of things into that.

00:24:59.980 --> 00:25:02.402
But [INAUDIBLE] has a
pretty big plane, as well.

00:25:02.402 --> 00:25:03.860
We arrived at one
summit on a plane

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:06.270
we borrowed from Led Zeppelin.

00:25:06.270 --> 00:25:11.700
And it had leopard skin
seats and stuff like that.

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:14.760
I think now the UK
prime minister is now

00:25:14.760 --> 00:25:16.120
allowed his own plane at last.

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:19.155
And about time, too.

00:25:19.155 --> 00:25:20.554
Long overdue.

00:25:20.554 --> 00:25:22.470
FEMALE SPEAKER: More
questions from the floor.

00:25:22.470 --> 00:25:24.840
Got one over here, please.

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:26.410
AUDIENCE: So we
see, as governments,

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:31.555
tend to lean more
on digital tools,

00:25:31.555 --> 00:25:33.320
that you enable them
to reach whatever

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:35.450
they got-- their goals.

00:25:35.450 --> 00:25:38.770
You know, with this whole
digital age thing coming about.

00:25:38.770 --> 00:25:44.030
How would you think the cyber
warfare aspect of things

00:25:44.030 --> 00:25:45.970
and the cyber espionage
type of things

00:25:45.970 --> 00:25:50.520
will affect diplomacy
and also the transparency

00:25:50.520 --> 00:25:54.087
within governments and
certain regimes, et cetera?

00:25:54.087 --> 00:25:55.920
TOM FLETCHER: It's a
really important point.

00:25:55.920 --> 00:26:00.710
And I think one of my great
worries is that, at the moment,

00:26:00.710 --> 00:26:07.250
as a result of Iraq, of Edward
Snowden, of Julian Assange,

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:12.756
the public doesn't actually
trust us enough with their data

00:26:12.756 --> 00:26:16.340
to give us the power
we need to take

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:20.510
on the bad guys in that space.

00:26:20.510 --> 00:26:22.620
And when we're
looking for evidence

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:25.260
of terrorist's planning and
so on, what we're looking for

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:26.220
is the needle in the haystack.

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:28.094
You've got to be able
to look through the hay

00:26:28.094 --> 00:26:29.064
in order to find it.

00:26:29.064 --> 00:26:31.230
And that's going to become
harder and harder because

00:26:31.230 --> 00:26:34.492
of that loss of
trust in government.

00:26:34.492 --> 00:26:35.950
And so somehow--
and it's something

00:26:35.950 --> 00:26:37.552
I'm trying to do
in the book a bit--

00:26:37.552 --> 00:26:39.510
somehow we have to try
and make the case afresh

00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:43.470
to people for why we can
be trusted-- why we're not

00:26:43.470 --> 00:26:45.780
some great kind of
Watergate-type conspiracy

00:26:45.780 --> 00:26:49.090
and all we really want to
do is read your emails.

00:26:49.090 --> 00:26:52.750
But I think we're losing
that argument at the moment.

00:26:52.750 --> 00:26:56.610
And that is a threat to
our collective survival

00:26:56.610 --> 00:26:59.770
because it gives an
advantage to people

00:26:59.770 --> 00:27:04.180
who want to threaten and
terrorize our societies.

00:27:04.180 --> 00:27:06.540
By the way though,
one of the best

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:09.660
follows I'd recommend on
Twitter at the moment is GCHQ.

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:11.660
CIA were great when they
first came on, as well.

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:15.690
But imagine if you're
trying to design a Twitter

00:27:15.690 --> 00:27:17.480
account for a spy agency.

00:27:17.480 --> 00:27:19.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:22.390
[INAUDIBLE] an interview
to try and challenge you.

00:27:22.390 --> 00:27:24.800
And the trick is, of
course, to just find

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:26.000
a way to be authentic.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.790
And GCHQ tweets math puzzles
and say, we love math.

00:27:30.790 --> 00:27:33.170
Can you try this out
and see if you're

00:27:33.170 --> 00:27:34.960
clever enough to work for us?

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:37.294
But also, they're proud of
their history, quite rightly.

00:27:37.294 --> 00:27:38.960
And so they tweet
stuff from the history

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:40.250
of-- that they can talk about.

00:27:40.250 --> 00:27:42.830
And I think that's a pretty
effective Twitter account.

00:27:42.830 --> 00:27:44.847
And if you like math
puzzles, they're great.

00:27:44.847 --> 00:27:46.180
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's fabulous.

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:48.580
I have a quick question about
the Official Secrets Act.

00:27:48.580 --> 00:27:51.280
So your book has gone through
the Official Secrets Act.

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:52.960
What was that like?

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:55.192
TOM FLETCHER: It wasn't too bad.

00:27:55.192 --> 00:27:57.650
Actually, I used to do this--
when I was inside government,

00:27:57.650 --> 00:27:59.108
one of the things
I used to oversee

00:27:59.108 --> 00:28:01.565
was clearing of books
by rogue diplomats.

00:28:01.565 --> 00:28:05.150
And so I kind of knew
where the line was.

00:28:05.150 --> 00:28:07.640
And I've taken out
lots of kind of very

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:11.570
salacious and racy stuff
from other people's books.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:15.150
Clearly, you can't talk
about specific examples

00:28:15.150 --> 00:28:17.270
of intelligence work.

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:18.372
FEMALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:28:18.372 --> 00:28:20.455
TOM FLETCHER: I think you
have to be a bit careful

00:28:20.455 --> 00:28:23.420
if you're talking about
serving leaders, quite rightly,

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:24.980
especially if you're
talking about--

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:27.645
if I was spilling the beans--
I'm sorry, it's not in here--

00:28:27.645 --> 00:28:29.270
it would make a more
interesting book--

00:28:29.270 --> 00:28:33.050
if I was spilling the beans
on what David Cameron thought

00:28:33.050 --> 00:28:35.270
of Angela Merkel.

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:37.409
I think someone in government
should take that out,

00:28:37.409 --> 00:28:37.950
to be honest.

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:41.930
Because that's not going to--
it's fun, it's salacious,

00:28:41.930 --> 00:28:45.040
but it's not going
to help anyone.

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:49.444
So I was trying to stay on
the right side of that line

00:28:49.444 --> 00:28:50.360
when I was writing it.

00:28:50.360 --> 00:28:52.568
In fact, in the end, the
one thing that got taken out

00:28:52.568 --> 00:28:55.950
was a reference
to representation.

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:57.930
And it's quite an
academic thing, this.

00:28:57.930 --> 00:29:02.080
I was saying I didn't feel I was
just Her Majesty's Ambassador,

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:03.030
HMA.

00:29:03.030 --> 00:29:05.810
But I felt like I was the
British people's ambassador.

00:29:05.810 --> 00:29:09.610
I was representing Bond,
and Beckham, and Benedict

00:29:09.610 --> 00:29:12.834
Cumberbatch, and
all the rest of it.

00:29:12.834 --> 00:29:16.440
And the feeling was
that that might not

00:29:16.440 --> 00:29:19.064
go down well with the palace.

00:29:19.064 --> 00:29:20.480
I've discussed it
with the palace.

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:22.000
They're quite relaxed.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.460
They do you feel that
that's what ambassadors do,

00:29:24.460 --> 00:29:26.150
you represent the
wider national brand.

00:29:26.150 --> 00:29:28.520
And that it's as important
to represent that soft power

00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:32.180
as it is to represent--
to judge your power by how

00:29:32.180 --> 00:29:33.385
many bullets you can sell.

00:29:33.385 --> 00:29:34.510
FEMALE SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:29:34.510 --> 00:29:35.780
More questions from the floor.

00:29:35.780 --> 00:29:38.520
AUDIENCE: So how do you
evaluate a diplomat?

00:29:38.520 --> 00:29:40.060
It was mentioned
in the introduction

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:43.464
that you were one of the
youngest ambassadors out there.

00:29:43.464 --> 00:29:45.755
I always imagine that diplomacy
is a very hierarchical,

00:29:45.755 --> 00:29:46.892
I guess, industry.

00:29:46.892 --> 00:29:47.850
There are no shortcuts.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:50.110
You have to do your
time as a junior attache

00:29:50.110 --> 00:29:54.156
in some [INAUDIBLE] country,
and again, and again, and so on.

00:29:54.156 --> 00:29:56.577
So can you comment on that?

00:29:56.577 --> 00:29:58.160
TOM FLETCHER: It is
very hierarchical.

00:29:58.160 --> 00:29:59.850
It's opening up.

00:29:59.850 --> 00:30:03.690
And so you've got lots of
slightly younger people coming

00:30:03.690 --> 00:30:05.024
through slightly earlier.

00:30:05.024 --> 00:30:06.940
Although, it's very
striking for me moving out

00:30:06.940 --> 00:30:08.270
of a business
where I always felt

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:09.853
I was the youngest
person in the room.

00:30:09.853 --> 00:30:11.750
And now, I'm kind of
doing things [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:11.750 --> 00:30:13.550
and I'm the oldest in the room.

00:30:16.424 --> 00:30:18.590
Much like anyone else, you
get evaluated every year.

00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:20.534
You get an annual appraisal.

00:30:20.534 --> 00:30:24.652
And they will look at
the key competencies.

00:30:24.652 --> 00:30:26.193
I guess you go
through similar thing.

00:30:26.193 --> 00:30:29.650
You had working with others,
leadership, problem-solving,

00:30:29.650 --> 00:30:30.647
and so on.

00:30:30.647 --> 00:30:32.730
I've just done a big review
of the Foreign Office.

00:30:32.730 --> 00:30:35.200
And what we're trying
to re-orientate towards

00:30:35.200 --> 00:30:36.810
is looking at the
skills as well.

00:30:36.810 --> 00:30:39.830
We've gone a bit too far in
the direction of competencies

00:30:39.830 --> 00:30:40.960
and away from the skills.

00:30:40.960 --> 00:30:42.610
So we need to get
back to evaluating

00:30:42.610 --> 00:30:44.870
people's courage, and
creativity, and curiosity,

00:30:44.870 --> 00:30:45.800
and so on.

00:30:45.800 --> 00:30:50.516
Those things that have always
made diplomats very, very good.

00:30:50.516 --> 00:30:52.390
You go through-- there's
an assessment center

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:54.770
kind of halfway through your
career, which is very, very

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:56.170
hard to get through.

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:57.590
Before you become
a diplomat, you

00:30:57.590 --> 00:31:00.130
have a year of being
tested and assessed.

00:31:00.130 --> 00:31:02.270
And they go out--
maybe this is something

00:31:02.270 --> 00:31:05.110
that Google in its terribly
sinister way is now doing.

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:08.470
But they used to go
out and talk to-- you'd

00:31:08.470 --> 00:31:11.479
give them three names from your
life of people who knew you.

00:31:11.479 --> 00:31:13.520
They would ask those three
people for three more,

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:14.850
and then, three
more, three more.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:17.130
They'd fan out until they got
to people who you didn't really

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:17.890
know.

00:31:17.890 --> 00:31:20.348
And then they would ask the
truth about what you were like.

00:31:20.348 --> 00:31:22.690
And then, they'd get you
back in and say, so that time

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:25.180
at that youth
hostel in Jerusalem,

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.540
on the roof when this happened--
and you'd be so shocked.

00:31:28.540 --> 00:31:30.350
The whole idea of
that was that they

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:32.764
wanted to ensure that you
weren't black mailable.

00:31:32.764 --> 00:31:34.180
They weren't going
to kick you out

00:31:34.180 --> 00:31:36.930
because you'd smoked
something funny at some stage

00:31:36.930 --> 00:31:39.820
or you'd spent the night with
someone funny at some stage.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:43.780
It was all about ensuring
they had all the information

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:46.800
that our opponents could
otherwise use to blackmail you.

00:31:49.174 --> 00:31:50.340
FEMALE SPEAKER: Fascinating.

00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:51.703
Question just behind.

00:31:51.703 --> 00:31:53.197
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
one of the things

00:31:53.197 --> 00:31:55.030
that struck me when you
were talking earlier

00:31:55.030 --> 00:31:57.350
about the culture that
you wanted to build

00:31:57.350 --> 00:31:59.580
seemed very similar to Google.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:01.080
We want a collaborative
environment.

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:03.410
And we're quite fanatical
about protecting that.

00:32:03.410 --> 00:32:05.300
And if we start to
see that it's shifting

00:32:05.300 --> 00:32:09.200
in one direction or another,
we have entire departments

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:10.340
dedicated to that.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:16.055
How do diplomats think
about shaping culture?

00:32:16.055 --> 00:32:17.430
And is there stuff
we could learn

00:32:17.430 --> 00:32:19.884
from you guys, or vice-versa?

00:32:19.884 --> 00:32:21.300
TOM FLETCHER: I
think actually one

00:32:21.300 --> 00:32:26.860
thing that British diplomats do
very well is share information.

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:28.910
You'd think in
most institutions,

00:32:28.910 --> 00:32:31.512
like the Foreign Office, there'd
be a hoarding of information.

00:32:31.512 --> 00:32:33.928
And that's the kind of classic,
kind of hierarchical thing

00:32:33.928 --> 00:32:35.000
to do.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:40.245
And I can pretty much guarantee
that this morning, our

00:32:40.245 --> 00:32:42.190
[INAUDIBLE], our
ambassador in New York,

00:32:42.190 --> 00:32:43.980
is going into the
Security Council

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:46.760
with more information than
anyone else in the room.

00:32:46.760 --> 00:32:49.435
Because he will have
read this morning

00:32:49.435 --> 00:32:50.810
reports-- we call
them telegrams,

00:32:50.810 --> 00:32:52.643
but they're really like
kind of long emails;

00:32:52.643 --> 00:32:57.650
they're not really telegrams--
from all the relevant countries

00:32:57.650 --> 00:32:59.787
that they're debating
that day in the hall.

00:32:59.787 --> 00:33:01.620
And he'll have got a
message from Number 10.

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:03.619
He'll have got messages
from the Foreign Office.

00:33:03.619 --> 00:33:06.750
And his people have
curated all that data

00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:09.420
in a way that means he's
got that head start.

00:33:09.420 --> 00:33:11.690
It's amazing how often,
as a British diplomat,

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:13.400
other diplomats come
to you to ask what's

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:15.560
happening in their
capital, because they're

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:18.160
hoarding information to
a much greater degree.

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:23.100
So that, I think, is perhaps
the key thing, the key strength

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:25.740
that I would try to
take from the world I

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:29.130
was in into other worlds.

00:33:29.130 --> 00:33:30.750
AUDIENCE: Does the
lobbying industry

00:33:30.750 --> 00:33:33.950
provide an effective diplomacy
channel for non-state actors

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:36.376
like Google to nation states?

00:33:38.895 --> 00:33:40.270
TOM FLETCHER: I
think it's making

00:33:40.270 --> 00:33:42.480
lots of people very rich.

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:45.620
I think there's lots that
I try to use in the book

00:33:45.620 --> 00:33:47.390
that we can learn from
watching lobbyists

00:33:47.390 --> 00:33:49.420
and how they operate
in order to be

00:33:49.420 --> 00:33:53.596
better diplomatic lobbyists,
which is one of the core things

00:33:53.596 --> 00:33:55.230
that we do.

00:33:55.230 --> 00:33:58.500
I was frustrated in Number
10 that in four years

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:00.150
I was lobbied a lot
by arms dealers,

00:34:00.150 --> 00:34:03.840
but I wasn't lobbied
anything like enough by NGOs.

00:34:03.840 --> 00:34:07.270
And yesterday, I went to talk
to a group of NGOs to say,

00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:08.949
here's how you can
be more effective.

00:34:08.949 --> 00:34:12.070
Here are the moments when
you can really change

00:34:12.070 --> 00:34:14.902
our views inside government.

00:34:14.902 --> 00:34:17.279
I think that lobbyists,
they wouldn't

00:34:17.279 --> 00:34:19.070
exist if they weren't
moderately effective.

00:34:19.070 --> 00:34:21.500
But they're much less
effective than they tell you

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:23.199
when they're pitching.

00:34:23.199 --> 00:34:25.880
AUDIENCE: You talked there
about summarizing information,

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:27.810
and Google's always
tried to make information

00:34:27.810 --> 00:34:29.770
accessible by
making it searchable

00:34:29.770 --> 00:34:33.090
so you can access everything
with the right search phrases.

00:34:33.090 --> 00:34:35.880
Whereas, what you
described for ambassadors

00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:38.670
was much more about really
effective summarization.

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:41.469
Do you think there's things
that either side could do better

00:34:41.469 --> 00:34:42.449
in that?

00:34:42.449 --> 00:34:43.240
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:34:43.240 --> 00:34:47.360
I mean, we're [? woeful ?]
at knowledge management.

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:50.600
And so when I used to go
and meet a Lebanese warlord,

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:53.290
he'd been there for
30 years and would

00:34:53.290 --> 00:34:54.955
have basically in
his head the kind

00:34:54.955 --> 00:34:56.580
of Rolodex of all
his previous contacts

00:34:56.580 --> 00:34:59.306
with British ambassadors.

00:34:59.306 --> 00:35:03.120
And I would be going in
there without any of that.

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:04.680
We haven't found
a really good way

00:35:04.680 --> 00:35:08.009
to conserve the data, the
knowledge that we have.

00:35:08.009 --> 00:35:09.550
And so again, one
of the things we're

00:35:09.550 --> 00:35:11.008
trying to do at
New York University

00:35:11.008 --> 00:35:14.080
now is build like a diplopedia,
which is almost your knowledge

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:16.800
archive as an institution.

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:19.480
And so that when
you go to a meeting,

00:35:19.480 --> 00:35:21.470
you have a kind of
diplobot, or an app,

00:35:21.470 --> 00:35:23.970
or a gadget that basically
runs through it and tells you,

00:35:23.970 --> 00:35:25.490
OK, this is the guy.

00:35:25.490 --> 00:35:27.180
10 years ago, he did this.

00:35:27.180 --> 00:35:29.500
15 years ago, he told
the ambassador this.

00:35:29.500 --> 00:35:31.380
This is the time
that he mucked up.

00:35:31.380 --> 00:35:33.190
This is the time that
he screwed us over.

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:35.106
This is the time that
he collaborated with us.

00:35:35.106 --> 00:35:37.810
And it just gives you
a much better sense

00:35:37.810 --> 00:35:42.029
of your historical relationship
with that individual.

00:35:42.029 --> 00:35:43.820
So that's something I
think we could really

00:35:43.820 --> 00:35:47.070
learn from the outside world.

00:35:47.070 --> 00:35:50.587
The reality is that Google
is doing that for us

00:35:50.587 --> 00:35:51.170
at the moment.

00:35:51.170 --> 00:35:55.726
Google is our best tool
for that at the moment.

00:35:55.726 --> 00:35:58.000
And yet, still inside the
Foreign Office-- I mean,

00:35:58.000 --> 00:35:58.530
this is the problem.

00:35:58.530 --> 00:36:00.905
If you Google "Naked Diplomat"
inside the Foreign Office,

00:36:00.905 --> 00:36:05.410
you get the hand saying
inappropriate content.

00:36:05.410 --> 00:36:07.750
But you find everyone
in the Foreign Office

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:09.066
using Google a huge amount.

00:36:09.066 --> 00:36:10.440
FEMALE SPEAKER:
It's interesting.

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:12.170
I think the question
really around how do you

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:13.607
summarize, and
collate, and access

00:36:13.607 --> 00:36:15.190
the right bits of
institutional memory

00:36:15.190 --> 00:36:17.920
at the right time is
absolutely incredible.

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:19.460
I think though,
it's very difficult,

00:36:19.460 --> 00:36:22.130
this warlord with
all of his memories.

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:25.462
If you were to look
at those in the whole,

00:36:25.462 --> 00:36:26.920
there'd be far too
much information

00:36:26.920 --> 00:36:29.370
to ever ingest or use usefully.

00:36:29.370 --> 00:36:31.865
It's the situational and
context clues, isn't it?

00:36:31.865 --> 00:36:32.130
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:36:32.130 --> 00:36:33.830
That's why if you can
be the person that

00:36:33.830 --> 00:36:35.930
can curate that
knowledge and work out

00:36:35.930 --> 00:36:39.241
what to do with it, that is
a position of real power now,

00:36:39.241 --> 00:36:39.740
I think.

00:36:39.740 --> 00:36:40.970
FEMALE SPEAKER: Interesting.

00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:43.810
AUDIENCE: You said you'd
talked about sending

00:36:43.810 --> 00:36:45.480
an ambassador to Google.

00:36:45.480 --> 00:36:47.890
And I guess the answer
was certainly not yet.

00:36:47.890 --> 00:36:52.290
What would be the trigger that
would actually make it happen?

00:36:52.290 --> 00:36:54.200
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:56.110
I mean, I think in
reality what would happen

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.550
is you'd send a representative.

00:36:57.550 --> 00:36:58.966
It wouldn't
necessarily be someone

00:36:58.966 --> 00:37:01.370
who would be called an
ambassador because that then

00:37:01.370 --> 00:37:04.680
basically suggests the
nation state is finished

00:37:04.680 --> 00:37:07.050
and you're looking at
different model, in which case,

00:37:07.050 --> 00:37:09.591
people would say, well, why is
it the British government that

00:37:09.591 --> 00:37:13.620
chooses to send one or not?

00:37:13.620 --> 00:37:15.790
I think what you will
see happening-- I mean,

00:37:15.790 --> 00:37:18.900
we already have a really
good consul general in LA,

00:37:18.900 --> 00:37:19.930
for example.

00:37:19.930 --> 00:37:24.960
I think you'll find that
those hubs near where

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:27.442
tech companies are will
grow and grow and grow.

00:37:27.442 --> 00:37:29.650
And you'll increasingly send
better and better people

00:37:29.650 --> 00:37:32.620
to those places because
it's a recognition

00:37:32.620 --> 00:37:34.870
that that's where
the arguments are

00:37:34.870 --> 00:37:36.170
and the potential ideas are.

00:37:36.170 --> 00:37:39.240
The problem for us
inside government

00:37:39.240 --> 00:37:42.560
is we still-- we're
still effectively saying

00:37:42.560 --> 00:37:44.822
to tech companies,
I think, OK, here

00:37:44.822 --> 00:37:46.030
are the issues we care about.

00:37:46.030 --> 00:37:48.070
Please come into
our conversation.

00:37:48.070 --> 00:37:51.400
And I imagine that that's
a bit of a turnoff.

00:37:51.400 --> 00:37:53.120
We've got to find
ways to say, OK,

00:37:53.120 --> 00:37:55.455
what are the things
we can crack together?

00:37:55.455 --> 00:37:59.670
What are the problems
we can solve together?

00:37:59.670 --> 00:38:01.105
But I don't know.

00:38:01.105 --> 00:38:02.730
This debate about
should Google come on

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:05.012
to the Security Council?

00:38:05.012 --> 00:38:07.647
That would be a trigger
to send someone to Google.

00:38:07.647 --> 00:38:10.515
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:10.515 --> 00:38:11.056
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:38:11.056 --> 00:38:13.410
You said that the
role of diplomats

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:17.800
is to foster cooperation
and sort of lightly touched

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:20.651
on the topic of Brexit.

00:38:20.651 --> 00:38:24.090
What do you think
about EU and what

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:26.670
would happen to
diplomacy if the UK were

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:27.940
to leave or not to leave?

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:29.520
What do you think should happen?

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:32.920
TOM FLETCHER: When
I used to advise PMs

00:38:32.920 --> 00:38:34.420
before press
conferences, I'd always

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.797
say, be careful towards the
end of the press conference

00:38:36.797 --> 00:38:38.380
because that's when
you start to relax

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:39.810
and that's when you kind
of let your guard down

00:38:39.810 --> 00:38:41.351
and give the answer you
weren't planning to.

00:38:41.351 --> 00:38:43.225
And this is the end of
the week of book tour.

00:38:43.225 --> 00:38:45.270
This is the last
event, actually.

00:38:45.270 --> 00:38:46.327
So I arrived conscious.

00:38:46.327 --> 00:38:47.910
All right, I'm not
going to go and say

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:51.080
the wrong thing on Brexit.

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:53.460
So forgive me for
being-- all my stuff

00:38:53.460 --> 00:38:55.580
is about being open
and honest and more

00:38:55.580 --> 00:38:57.439
transparent about what we do.

00:38:57.439 --> 00:38:59.230
Except when it comes
to my views on Brexit,

00:38:59.230 --> 00:39:01.610
where I've spent the whole
week trying not to answer

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:03.192
that question.

00:39:03.192 --> 00:39:06.927
I'm really worried about
the way the debate has gone.

00:39:06.927 --> 00:39:09.010
I don't think that Britain
is a country that needs

00:39:09.010 --> 00:39:10.093
to be scared of the world.

00:39:10.093 --> 00:39:14.050
And the debate, I
fear, on both sides

00:39:14.050 --> 00:39:17.960
has been much-- far too
much characterized by fear.

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:21.100
We must leave Europe because
those terribly frightening

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:24.762
people in Brussels are
dominating our lives.

00:39:24.762 --> 00:39:26.970
Or, we must stay in Europe
because if we don't, we'll

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:28.420
never survive in
the 21st century.

00:39:28.420 --> 00:39:32.240
I don't believe
either of those views.

00:39:32.240 --> 00:39:36.030
The country I was representing--
trying to represent in Lebanon

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:37.960
was much more confident,
and outward-looking,

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:42.549
and aware of its role in
the world and its history.

00:39:42.549 --> 00:39:45.700
We've been at our best when
we've been outward-looking,

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:51.046
and open-minded, and sought
new ideas and markets.

00:39:51.046 --> 00:39:53.254
You see, I'm not answering
the question at all, am I?

00:39:53.254 --> 00:39:54.182
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:54.182 --> 00:40:01.180
But as I said earlier on, I'm
up for coexistence and opposed

00:40:01.180 --> 00:40:02.330
to building walls.

00:40:02.330 --> 00:40:05.352
And so that gives
you a bit of a clue.

00:40:05.352 --> 00:40:06.284
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:06.284 --> 00:40:09.850
I should explain why I'm not
answering the question, which

00:40:09.850 --> 00:40:12.941
is that we're in a period
called Purdah where

00:40:12.941 --> 00:40:15.030
current civil servants
and recently resigned

00:40:15.030 --> 00:40:17.460
civil servants aren't
supposed to give

00:40:17.460 --> 00:40:19.355
a view on the referendum.

00:40:19.355 --> 00:40:21.230
So, sorry, that's why
I have to be so boring.

00:40:21.230 --> 00:40:23.605
FEMALE SPEAKER: If we perhaps
took a step back and looked

00:40:23.605 --> 00:40:25.330
at things a little
bit more abstractly,

00:40:25.330 --> 00:40:31.880
as opposed to talking about
Brexit directly-- let's just

00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:33.567
say we took one step back.

00:40:33.567 --> 00:40:35.150
TOM FLETCHER: You
should be on the TV.

00:40:35.150 --> 00:40:36.461
This is [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:36.461 --> 00:40:38.210
FEMALE SPEAKER: You
know, I do what I can.

00:40:38.210 --> 00:40:43.165
But I have a genuine question
around unpicking the EU,

00:40:43.165 --> 00:40:45.500
or unpicking any set of
complicated agreements

00:40:45.500 --> 00:40:48.850
is probably outside of
something I'm capable of doing

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:50.369
as an informed citizen.

00:40:50.369 --> 00:40:51.160
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:54.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: So if we're
looking at not Brexit,

00:40:54.110 --> 00:40:57.560
but a complicated set
of external engagements

00:40:57.560 --> 00:41:00.656
and agreements, what's the
role for citizen diplomacy

00:41:00.656 --> 00:41:01.780
or citizen democracy there?

00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:04.480
How can we meaningfully
and relevantly engage?

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:07.600
And to what extent can we
meaningfully or relevantly

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:08.622
engage?

00:41:08.622 --> 00:41:10.300
TOM FLETCHER: It's
true, actually.

00:41:10.300 --> 00:41:12.200
I mean, I think
that's, in a way,

00:41:12.200 --> 00:41:15.370
a reason why either
outcome actually

00:41:15.370 --> 00:41:18.900
will have lots of officials
kind of licking their lips,

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:22.150
because there will be a
real job for them to do.

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:25.420
And in a situation where
we, for example, we

00:41:25.420 --> 00:41:28.166
were dealing with Brexit,
there'd be masses of work.

00:41:28.166 --> 00:41:29.540
And yet, it would
have to be done

00:41:29.540 --> 00:41:32.410
by the professional diplomats.

00:41:32.410 --> 00:41:35.530
So they would be at
the center of things,

00:41:35.530 --> 00:41:37.130
actually, in that context.

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:39.582
FEMALE SPEAKER: But how can
citizens make those choices

00:41:39.582 --> 00:41:40.165
and decisions?

00:41:43.932 --> 00:41:45.640
TOM FLETCHER: That's
a really good point.

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:51.360
I would hope that anyone
running that negotiation

00:41:51.360 --> 00:41:54.150
would be trying to find ways to
engage people and involve them

00:41:54.150 --> 00:41:57.006
more in the decisions
we would need to take,

00:41:57.006 --> 00:42:01.640
so that it wouldn't all
be done behind the curtain

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:04.460
by the institutions.

00:42:04.460 --> 00:42:07.550
But I think also,
as individuals,

00:42:07.550 --> 00:42:10.020
you would need to be challenging
government at that moment.

00:42:10.020 --> 00:42:15.550
And saying, that vote--
whichever way the Brexit

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:18.696
vote goes, the public have
basically been saying,

00:42:18.696 --> 00:42:21.600
we're fed up of everything
we've stitched up in this way.

00:42:21.600 --> 00:42:25.140
We want more of a say
over where power is going

00:42:25.140 --> 00:42:26.250
and how it's exercised.

00:42:26.250 --> 00:42:27.750
So hopefully that
gives people a bit

00:42:27.750 --> 00:42:29.934
more leverage with
government to hold

00:42:29.934 --> 00:42:32.100
them to account and to
influence specific decisions,

00:42:32.100 --> 00:42:34.464
rather than waiting every
five years for an election.

00:42:34.464 --> 00:42:35.380
FEMALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:37.921
TOM FLETCHER: But that's going
to take more direct democracy.

00:42:37.921 --> 00:42:40.320
FEMALE SPEAKER: Time for
another two questions.

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:42.960
One in the back row.

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:49.050
AUDIENCE: Can you follow
up about agreements

00:42:49.050 --> 00:42:53.910
like TTIP that are being
negotiated in secret and people

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:57.290
do not really have any
influence about that?

00:42:57.290 --> 00:43:00.460
And a second one would
be similar to this

00:43:00.460 --> 00:43:03.940
because-- and touching
also on the surveillance--

00:43:03.940 --> 00:43:06.940
because we have seen in the
past that surveillance has

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:11.110
been abused time and again
to actually stop people

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:13.360
from having an influence.

00:43:13.360 --> 00:43:15.079
So can you comment
on that please?

00:43:15.079 --> 00:43:15.870
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:43:15.870 --> 00:43:17.425
I mean, I think
on the second one,

00:43:17.425 --> 00:43:19.630
it comes back to the point
about how difficult it

00:43:19.630 --> 00:43:25.040
is for us to build the trust we
need to keep people secure now.

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:27.390
Because we don't
have a great history

00:43:27.390 --> 00:43:30.911
of doing it in the right way.

00:43:30.911 --> 00:43:32.410
I mean, generally,
in my experience,

00:43:32.410 --> 00:43:39.141
having been in that world,
if you go down to Cheltenham,

00:43:39.141 --> 00:43:41.640
where we have our government
communication headquarters that

00:43:41.640 --> 00:43:45.870
does the monitoring
work, you will

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:48.260
find a bunch of people who
are incredibly motivated,

00:43:48.260 --> 00:43:54.890
and real public servants,
and very professional.

00:43:54.890 --> 00:43:59.460
And I just wish there was a
way of almost demonstrating

00:43:59.460 --> 00:44:02.640
that more effectively, of
showing that, actually, there

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:05.610
are strong values at the heart
of many of these institutions.

00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:07.790
But it's a very
difficult argument

00:44:07.790 --> 00:44:10.620
to win while being
secretive about--

00:44:10.620 --> 00:44:14.526
and [INAUDIBLE] be
secretive about what you do.

00:44:14.526 --> 00:44:17.239
There will always be a role
for secrecy in the negotiations

00:44:17.239 --> 00:44:18.030
on the first point.

00:44:18.030 --> 00:44:21.770
And there's always a role--
the Iran deal was done mainly

00:44:21.770 --> 00:44:22.800
in secret.

00:44:22.800 --> 00:44:25.240
You know, I wasn't in the
room live tweeting the Iran

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:27.930
deal-- just as well.

00:44:27.930 --> 00:44:29.780
So there is still
a part of diplomacy

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:31.550
which has to be confidential.

00:44:31.550 --> 00:44:33.926
Just as, you know, there's
a part of your world

00:44:33.926 --> 00:44:35.800
when you're negotiating
to buy a company that

00:44:35.800 --> 00:44:38.740
has to be done in secret.

00:44:38.740 --> 00:44:43.764
And that won't go
away any time soon.

00:44:43.764 --> 00:44:45.180
My argument in the
book is that we

00:44:45.180 --> 00:44:47.676
have to find a way to
try to explain that,

00:44:47.676 --> 00:44:49.630
to communicate with
people to explain

00:44:49.630 --> 00:44:51.690
why it has to be secret,
rather than just saying,

00:44:51.690 --> 00:44:53.730
it's all a bit too complicated.

00:44:53.730 --> 00:44:55.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:44:55.110 --> 00:44:56.880
One more question.

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:01.110
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
citizen diplomacy before.

00:45:01.110 --> 00:45:03.220
What would you recommend,
or what is there

00:45:03.220 --> 00:45:08.410
that we can actually do now to
fight against building walls

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:11.890
and our ideas for the world?

00:45:11.890 --> 00:45:12.890
FEMALE SPEAKER: Amazing.

00:45:12.890 --> 00:45:13.960
Amazing to finish on.

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:15.959
TOM FLETCHER: Yeah,
brilliant note to finish on.

00:45:15.959 --> 00:45:18.440
I think, pick the
right argument.

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:21.092
Take on the people who are on
the wrong side of the argument.

00:45:21.092 --> 00:45:23.300
Think about how you can use
the smartphone superpower

00:45:23.300 --> 00:45:26.590
that you have to get into
those debates in the right way.

00:45:26.590 --> 00:45:31.120
Don't just assume that someone
else will do that for you.

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:33.510
But you're doing
this all already.

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:35.760
I mean, being kind of
curious and open-minded

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:38.170
about the world, and
taking on those people who

00:45:38.170 --> 00:45:41.899
are getting more and more
narrow and introverted.

00:45:41.899 --> 00:45:43.065
Joining the right campaigns.

00:45:47.490 --> 00:45:50.417
As you are doing,
building the ideas

00:45:50.417 --> 00:45:52.750
